BodyFat prediction with multiple linear regression - R

ABSTRACT

In the following research we present an analysis of the âBodyfatâ dataset. The purpose of the project is to be able to predict the body fat percentage using easily obtainable physical measures. The dataset is explored and then divided into a training set containing the 80% of the initial observations, chosen randomly, and a test set containing the remaining 20%. Subsequently, a descriptive analysis of the training-set is carried out, paying particular attention to the correlation between the variables collected in it. Several regression models are then developed and compared.

1. DATASET DESCRIPTION

The dataset consists of 251 observations relating to 15 attributes. More specifically:

  • Density determined from underwater weighing
  • Percent body fat from Siriâs (1956) equation (target variable)
  • Age (years)
  • Weight (pnd)
  • Height (inches)
  • Neck circumference (cm)
  • Chest circumference (cm)
  • Abdomen circumference (cm)
  • Hip circumference (cm)
  • Thigh circumference (cm)
  • Knee circumference (cm)
  • Ankle circumference (cm)
  • Biceps (extended) circumference (cm)
  • Forearm circumference (cm)
  • Wrist circumference (cm)

The body fat percentage is calculated from the Density variable using the following equation:

\(\%\) \(BodyFat\) \(=\) \((\frac{495}{Density}) - 450\)

There is therefore a direct linear relationship between BodyFat and \(Density ^ {- 1}\), making the use of Density as an explanatory variable in a regression model insignificant. Density will in any case be used for a comparison with the regression model consisting of the variables concerning physical measurements.

2. LIBRARIES USED

The following libraries were used:

  • fBasics: basicStats function for a summary of the main statistical values.

  • tidyverse: package containing various graphic and organizational utilities. In particular:

    • ggplot2: library for the creation and the manipulation of graphics.
    • ggthemes: library used for a purely aesthetic improvement of graphics.
    • dplyr: library for data management.

  • gridExtra: grid.arrange function for multiple presentation of graphs created with ggplot2.

  • ggpubr: library containing further graphic and textual utilities.

  • corrplot: library used for the creation of correlation graphs.

  • MASS: library containing the stepAIC function, which makes a stepwise selection of the model.

  • lindia: gg_qplot function for a better visualization of the Normal-QQ Plot.

  • knitr: library containing utilities for graphical display of tables in R-Markdown.

The dataset has no null values.

In order to identify inconsistent values we proceed as follows:

  • Letâs display the scatter plot between \(Density ^ {- 1}\) and BodyFat. In accordance with the previous relation the points should be substantially aligned in such a way as to form a straight line.

  • In the dataset there are inconsistent measurements (e.g.Â subject 75 cm tall with a weight of about 120 kg). Letâs display the box plots of the variables Height, Weight and Ankle, in order to identify and remove them.

From the graph we can see 4 inconsistent observations, which turn out to be:

  • 48
  • 76
  • 96
  • 182

We proceed removing them.

bodyfat <- bodyfat[-c(48, 76, 96, 182), ]

So letâs consider the box plots of Height, Weight and Ankle.

There are four extremely anomalous observations, i.e.Â those related to:

  • Subject with Height approximately equal to 75 cm.
  • Subject with Weight approximately equal to 160 kg.
  • Subjects with Ankle approximately equal to 35 cm.

So letâs proceed with their removal and check the box plots of the remaining variables.

No further inconsistent observations can be found from the previous box plots. The analysis of the anomalous values will be addressed in the regression phase.

3.4 One-factor analysis

Before studying in detail the correlations between the variables of the dataset (in particular with the target), we investigate the possible dependence in mean between the age of the subjects and the percentage of body fat.

A column Age_Group with three modalities is added:

  • Young (Age \(<\) 30)
  • Adult (30 \(<\) Age \(<\) 60)
  • Senior (Age \(\ge\) 60)

Letâs see if the target variable BodyFat is influenced by belonging to a certain age group.

As can be seen from the previous graphs, both the mean and the median of BodyFat are the highest in correspondence of the Old range, while they are the lowest for the Young range. The within-group variability appears to be comparable, as also deduced from the Bartlett test.

bartlett.test(bodyfat_order_age$BodyFat,bodyfat_order_age$Age_Group)
## 
##  Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  bodyfat_order_age$BodyFat and bodyfat_order_age$Age_Group
## Bartlett's K-squared = 2.6151, df = 2, p-value = 0.2705

Before proceeding with the one-factor analysis of variance, letâs verify the normality of the data in the various groups, by using qqnorm and the values of skewness and kurtosis.

BodyFat_Young BodyFat_Adult BodyFat_Old
skewness 0.536999 0.278809 -0.519809
kurtosis -0.605540 0.051823 -0.757190

The values in the table of skewness and kurtosis, the qqplots and what has already been shown regarding the variance of the groups show the applicability of the hypotheses of normality and homoskedasticity.

Similar considerations can be made by observing the following graph, which shows the density functions of BodyFat with respect to the three groups. The centers of the latter, in the dispersion diagram, show an increasing trend as the age group increases.

So letâs apply the single factor hypothesis test.

oneway.test(bodyfat_order_age$BodyFat ~ bodyfat_order_age$Age_Group, var.equal = TRUE)
## 
##  One-way analysis of means
## 
## data:  bodyfat_order_age$BodyFat and bodyfat_order_age$Age_Group
## F = 15.046, num df = 2, denom df = 241, p-value = 6.959e-07
qf(0.95,2,244)
## [1] 3.032816

The previous results lead to the rejection of the null hypothesis: the value of the calculated F-statistic is greater than the threshold of the critical region.

We can therefore conclude by stating that there is dependence in mean between the age group and the percentage of body fat.

3.5 Train-test split

Now we divide the dataset into two different parts: a training set (80%) and a test set (20%). The selection is computed randomly using the sample function.

set.seed(123)
train = sample(1:nrow(bodyfat), size = 0.8 * nrow(bodyfat))
bodyfat.train = bodyfat[train, -c(16)]
bodyfat.test = bodyfat[-train, -c(16)]

From the two previous graphical representations we can assume that the variables correlated the most to BodyFat (not considering Density) are, in order:

Analyzing the correlation matrix associated with the identified variables, it can be observed that these are also very correlated with each other.

In particular, in order to build a regression model, the correlations between the first 4 variables related the most to BodyFat turn out to be problematic.

Let us now try to distinguish whether the correlation with the target variable is direct or due to some relationship between the internal variables, i.e.Â whether or not we have spurious correlations.

From the previous tables we can substantially observe that only the correlation of the variable Abdomen with BodyFat is poorly influenced by the correlation between Abdomen and the other variables.

Instead, the correlation between Weight and BodyFat can be almost totally explained by Chest. Similarly, the correlation between Chest and BodyFat can be almost totally explained by Abdomen and the correlation between Hip and BodyFat depends almost entirely on the correlation between Hip and the other variables.

4 MULTIPLE LINEAR REGRESSION

4.1 Variable selection

We face the problem of multiple linear regression starting from the considerations made previously about the correlations between the dataset variables.

Meanwhile, letâs consider the variables most related to BodyFat (\(\ge\) 0.5), i.e.Â Abdomen, Chest, Weight, Hip, Thigh, Neck, Knee e Biceps.

The high correlation between these variables and BodyFat leads to the so-called multicollinearity problem. So letâs try to deal with it as follows:

  • The variable Weight is more related to the other covariates than to BodyFat itself and, as already noted, its correlation with BodyFat is almost entirely explained by the one with Abdomen. So letâs remove this variable;

  • Abdomen and Chest are the covariates most related to the target variable, however there is a strong correlation between them. Therefore, we introduce their relationship (AbCh) as an explanatory variable.

The AbCh variable is highly correlated to BodyFat and the multicollinearity problem has been reduced. However, we can make a further selection:

  • Abdomen and AbCh are obviously very related. We remove Abdomen;
  • After Abdomen, Hip is the covariate most related to AbCh (and to the other covariates). We also remove Hip.

Although it still exists, the problem of multicollinearity has been reduced.

4.2 The regression model

For the initial building of the regression model we use the three covariates related the most to BodyFat (AbCh, Chest and Thigh), leaving momentarily aside Neck, Knee and Biceps.

Now letâs choose the regression model. We use the stepAIC function for a stepwise selection of the model, given the target variable BodyFat and the covariates AbCh, Chest and Thigh.

The residual scatter plot has a smooth trend around 0, showing a linear relationship. This therefore does not suggest the introduction of a term, for example, quadratic or cubic.

The quantile-quantile diagram, on the other hand, presents a line that follows the trend of the points representing the standardized residuals, with the exception of the tails, where the points are moderately distant from the line.

5 PREDICTION AND COMPARISON WITH DENSITY

We evaluate, through the test set, the predictive capabilities of this model, comparing them with the model built using Density as single covariate.

5.1 Prediction

We check the percentage of âcorrectlyâ predicted values with five different percentages of margin (tolerance). Then, we plot the difference, in absolute value, between predicted values and real values.

The dashed red lines represent the endpoint of the prediction range, i.e.Â the uncertainty around the single predicted values. The band around the regression line (in blue) represents the uncertainty around the average forecasts. In both cases, the confidence/tolerance level is 95%.

The data points of the graph are all included between the two dashed red lines. Furthermore, the percentages of correctly predicted values, in relation to the results obtained during the training phase, are excellent. In particular, the model is able to predict 84% of the values with a tolerance of 25% and 72% with a tolerance of 5%, using measurements that are much more convenient to obtain than the density measured underwater.

6 CONCLUSION

In summary, we carried out the descriptive analysis of the BodyFat dataset, thanks to which it was verified that the percentage of bodyfat is dependent in mean on the age group of an individual. Additionally, a linear regression model was built to predict body fat percentage. The model constructed was then compared with the model having as its only covariate the variable Density, which (obviously) has a very high precision, but it makes use of a regressor (Density) which is much more difficult to obtain than the less precise common body measurements. The regression model having the latter as covariates is however quite reliable, with an R-squared index of about 75% and, above all, a predictive capacity of 86% with a tolerance of 25%, which falls âonlyâ to 72% in case of tolerance of 5%. In conclusion, this model represents a good compromise between performance and complexity of the measurements.

APPENDIX: FUNCTIONS IMPLEMENTED

For the purposes of a better understanding and an optimization of the code, various functions have been implemented. In particular:

  • udm(var_name): Purely accessory function that associates its own unit of measurement to each variable in the graphs.

  • Unit conversion:

    • from_inches_to_cm(x): Inches -> Centimeters.
    • from_pnd_to_kg(x): Pounds -> Kilograms.
  • date_scatter(xvar, yvar, dataset): Function that takes a variable xvar as input and returns a grob with the informations necessary to create the relative scatter plot, with respect to the target BodyFat (yvar).
  • date_box(xvar): Function that takes a variable xvar as input and returns a grob with the informations necessary to create the relative box plot.
  • partial_correlation(x, y, z): Function that returns the partial correlation between x and y, given z.
  • graphs_(model, residuals, name): Function which, given a model, returns the graphs concerning the analysis of the linear model with residual annexes.
  • prediction(model, err): Function that returns the percentage of test set values correctly predicted by the model passed as a parameter. In particular, the percentage is calculated considering the ratio between correct forecasts and total forecasts, where by ârightâ we mean an error margin equal to err.
  • prediction_graph(model): Function that, given a model, returns the graph concerning the difference between predicted and actual values, based on the test set.
